jtxt.emulator.tui

Class Table

  • java.lang.Object
    • jtxt.emulator.tui.Component
      • jtxt.emulator.tui.Container<Table.Column>
        • jtxt.emulator.tui.Table
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<Component>

    public class Table
extends Container<Table.Column>
    A Container which organizes its children into rows and columns. This Container can be used to easily align a collection of Components on both of their axes. (Components which have the same row or column number will be aligned along an axis.)
    See Also:
    Container, GridLayout

    • Field Detail

      • grid

        protected GridLayout grid
        The Layout used for this table. Since tables are very closely related to the GridLayout, we use much of the functionality already written for this layout manager when drawing the Components of this Container.

    • Constructor Detail

      • Table

        public Table(java.lang.Object parameters,
             int rows,
             int columns)
        Creates a new Table which organizes it's children into a grid of rows and columns. A Table is similar to the GridLayout, but allows for insertion of rows and columns at runtime, and which makes it more convenient to group related children in a structured fashion.
        Parameters:
        parameters - The layout parameters for this Container.
        rows - The initial number of rows in this Table.
        columns - The initial number of columns in this Table.

    • Method Detail

      • createColumn

        protected Table.Column createColumn(int columnNumber)
        Creates a new Column which can be inserted into the Table for the given column number, using the number of rows to determine the number of components it can hold.
        Parameters:
        columnNumber - The position within the Table that this column will occupy.
        Returns:
        A new Column for the given columnNumber.

      • add

        public void add(int rowNumber,
                int columnNumber,
                Component... components)
        Adds the given Components to this Table, where the row and column number determine where the first Component will appear, and all subsequent Components will follow the first in the column. If the number of Components passed into this method are greater than the number of rows allocated within that column, an exception will be thrown.
        Parameters:
        rowNumber - The row number of the first Component to add.
        columnNumber - The column number of the first Component to add.
        components - The Components to add to this Table.
        See Also:
        #insertIntoColumn(int, int, boolean, Component...)

      • insertIntoColumn

        public void insertIntoColumn(int rowNumber,
                             int columnNumber,
                             Component... components)
        Inserts the given Components into this table at the specified row and column, shifting any elements within that column downward to accommodate these new elements.
        Parameters:
        rowNumber - The row that the Components should be inserted before.
        columnNumber - The column that the Components should be inserted in.
        after - Whether to insert the Components into the column before or after the given indices. (If false, then the Components will occupy the position specified; otherwise, the Component which was at that position before will be retained, while all Components that followed it will have been shifted.)
        components - The Components to insert before the row and column.
